{
  "text": "Mutant survival in mice. Deletion mutants were made of the loci associated with the identified promoter regions, and deletions were replaced by an antibiotic resistance marker. If the promoters appeared to be linked to an operon, the first gene of that operon was mutated. In the case of clone 723, two mutants were made: CFT073 irp2 and CFT073 fyuA. The former gene encodes a yersiniabactin synthesis enzyme, whereas the latter encodes an outer membrane yersiniabactin uptake receptor. Both are transcribed from the same promoter in a long operon in the Yersinia enterocolitica high-pathogenicity island (HPI) [CITATION_1] . In the case of clone 301, the degS locus could not be deleted by the Red method, but a single crossover disruption mutation could be made (see above).",
